<hr /></div>

<div id="main-text">

<h2 id="BrieChroFeyeLifeWork">1. A Brief Chronology of Feyerabend&rsquo;s Life and Work</h2>

<p>
Feyerabend led an extraordinarily eventful life, interacting directly
with several prominent philosophers and scientists, most notably Karl
Popper, Ludwig Wittgenstein, Niels Bohr, and David Bohm, who became
significant influences on the development of his views.
Feyerabend&rsquo;s formative development is best seen against the
backdrop of his tumultuous relationship with his mentor Karl Popper,
Initially, Feyerabend was an ardent supporter of Popper&rsquo;s
philosophy of science (&lsquo;falsificationism&rsquo;) and his broader
philosophy (&lsquo;critical rationalism&rsquo;). In 1962, Feyerabend
began to criticize falsificationism while continuing to support
critical rationalism. After an epiphany, in private letters sent on
the 17th of December 1967, Feyerabend broke with Popper&rsquo;s
school, generalizing from the limited validity of falsificationism to
&ldquo;anything goes&rdquo; (the limited validity of all
methodological rules). He reversed himself on realism from
recommending correcting common knowledge and everyday language with
science to protecting common knowledge and everyday language from
scientism, abandoning his earlier project, and beginning his later
work. He repeatedly redeveloped his views on meaning and method,
making them relevant to a broad range of controversial issues, from
his relativism in political philosophy in the late 1970s and 1980s, to
his post-modernism in the 1990s.</p>

<table class="cellpad-small jfy vert-top">
<tbody>
<tr>
  <td>1924</td>
  <td>Born in Vienna. Son of a civil servant and a seamstress.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>1940</td>
  <td>After indoctrination in the Hitler youth, inducted into the
<em>Arbeitsdienst</em> (the work service introduced by the
Nazis).</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1942</td>
  <td>Drafted into the Pioneer Corps of the German army. After basic
training, volunteered for Officers&rsquo; School.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1943</td>
  <td>Learns of his mother&rsquo;s suicide.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1944</td>
  <td>Decorated, Iron Cross. Advances to Lieutenant. Lectures to
Officers&rsquo; School.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1945</td>
  <td>Shot in the hand and the belly while retreating from the Russian
Army, rendering him paralyzed from the waist down.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1946</td>
  <td>Receives fellowship to study singing and stage management in
Weimar. Joins the &ldquo;Cultural Association for the Democratic
Reform of Germany&rdquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1947</td>
  <td>Returns to Vienna to study history and sociology at the
University. Transfers to physics, but eventually settles for
philosophy (taking philosophy courses in all eight semesters).
Initially &ldquo;a raving positivist&rdquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1948</td>
  <td>First visits the Alpbach International Summer Seminar of the
Austrian College Society (European Forum Alpbach). Becomes secretary
and short-hand writer of the philosophy of science seminar. First
essay (grey literature) on Schrodinger&rsquo;s views on
<em>Anschaulichkeit</em> [visualizability] in modern physics. Meets
and immediately takes to Karl Popper. Befriends Walter Hollitscher.
Marries first wife, Edeltrud.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1949</td>
  <td>Assists the contentious experimental physicist, Felix Ehrenhaft.
Witnesses the impotence of Ehrenhaft&rsquo;s experimental effects,
raising problems of empiricism. Founds, as student leader, the
&ldquo;Kraft Circle&rdquo; (&lsquo;third Vienna Circle&rsquo;), a
science-student philosophy club, under Viktor Kraft, who became
Feyerabend&rsquo;s dissertation supervisor. Befriends Elizabeth
Anscombe. Meets Ludwig Wittgenstein, who participated in a meeting at
Feyerabend&rsquo;s invitation.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1950</td>
  <td>Meets Ludwig Wittgenstein, who participated in a meeting of the
Kraft Circle at Feyerabend&rsquo;s invitation to discuss
Popper&rsquo;s &lsquo;basic statements&rsquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1951</td>
  <td><em>&ldquo;Zur</em> <em>Theorie der Basiss&auml;tze</em>&rdquo;
[On the theory of basic statements] (Ph.D. thesis). Having
unsuccessfully attempted a Ph.D. in theoretical physics, settles for a
doctorate in philosophy developed from his Kraft Circle notes.
Receives British Council scholarship to study foundations of quantum
theory under Popper.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1952</td>
  <td>Arrives in England to study under Popper at the London School of
Economics. Concentrates on the quantum theory and Wittgenstein.
Studies the typescript of Wittgenstein&rsquo;s <em>Philosophical
Investigations</em>, and prepares a summary of the book. Befriends
another of Popper&rsquo;s students, Joseph Agassi.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1953</td>
  <td>Returns to Vienna. Popper had applied for an extension to his
scholarship, but Feyerabend decides to remain in Vienna instead.
Begins translation of Popper&rsquo;s &lsquo;war effort&rsquo; (<em>The
Open Society and its Enemies</em>). Declines an offer to become
Popper&rsquo;s research assistant. Becomes assistant to Arthur Pap in
Vienna.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1954</td>
  <td>Publishes lengthy critical reconstruction of
Wittgenstein&rsquo;s <em>Investigations</em> and &lsquo;<em>Physik und
Ontologie&rsquo;</em> [Physics and Ontology], setting out his
conception of scientific philosophy based on the dynamic relation
between science and philosophy. Pap introduces him to Herbert Feigl,
who becomes central to promoting Feyerabend&rsquo;s professional
development. Publishes (in German) another five short reviews of books
on formal logic and the foundations of mathematics.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1955</td>
  <td>&ldquo;<em>Carnaps Theorie der Interpretation theoretischer
Systeme</em>&rdquo; [Carnap&rsquo;s theory of the interpretation of
theoretical systems] launches his oft-repeated criticism of the
logical positivist view. Publishes Anscombe&rsquo;s translation of his
two-part critical review of Wittgenstein&rsquo;s
<em>Investigations</em> (first English publication). Begins first
full-time academic appointment as lecturer in philosophy at the
University of Bristol, England.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1956</td>
  <td>&ldquo;A Note on the Paradox of Analysis&rdquo; criticizes
analytic philosophy. &ldquo;<em>Eine Bemerkung zum Neumannschen
Beweis</em>&rdquo; [A Remark on von Neumann&rsquo;s Proof] temporarily
adopts Popper&rsquo;s views on indeterminism in foundations of quantum
mechanics reversing himself. Popper accuses him of plagiarism. Marries
second wife, Mary O&rsquo;Neill.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1957</td>
  <td>&ldquo;On the Quantum-Theory of Measurement&rdquo; reverts to
his earlier Bohrian view on the foundations of quantum mechanics.
Befriends David Bohm, who increasingly becomes a substantial
influence, especially concerning his criticism of Popper&rsquo;s
empiricism, his repeated pleas for more tolerance and pluralism in
science, his &lsquo;ever-increasing ocean of alternatives&rsquo;
conception of progress, and his ontological pluralism given the
&lsquo;non-autonomy of facts&rsquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1958</td>
  <td>&ldquo;An Attempt at a Realistic Interpretation of
Experience&rdquo; summarizes the ideas developed in his 1951 Ph.D.
thesis, setting out his conception of what good science should be.
&ldquo;Complementarity&rdquo; applies his methodological views to the
foundations of quantum theory. Begins visiting lectureship at the
University of California, Berkeley.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1959</td>
  <td>Accepts a permanent position at Berkeley. Applies for a Green
Card to work in the US.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1960</td>
  <td>&ldquo;<em>Das Problem der Existenz theoretischer
Entit&auml;ten</em>&rdquo; [The Problem of the Existence of
Theoretical Entities] argues that there is no special
&lsquo;problem&rsquo; of theoretical entities because <em>all</em>
entities are theoretical. &ldquo;Science without Foundations&rdquo;
embroiders on Popper&rsquo;s views about the pre-Socratics based on
two lectures he gave at Oberlin College, Ohio.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1961</td>
  <td>Meets Thomas Kuhn. Severely criticizes a draft of <em>The
Structure of Scientific Revolutions</em>, leading to a major rift in
their relations that lasted until 1983.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1962</td>
  <td>&ldquo;Explanation, Reduction, and Empiricism&rdquo; combines
Popper&rsquo;s views on testability with Wittgenstein&rsquo;s insight
that one observation sentence makes two incompatible statements
depending on which theory is used to interpret it. Launches his
often-repeated methodological argument for theoretical pluralism:
Sometimes an anomaly can refute an established theory only after the
invention of an alternative incommensurable explanation of it, as
illustrated by Einstein&rsquo;s prediction of Brownian motion.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td>1963</td>
  <td>&ldquo;How to be a Good Empiricist&rdquo; simplifies and
summarizes his views, arguing that contemporary empiricism
(Popper&rsquo;s included) needs to be disinfected of its empirical
core, given the meaning variance that results from scientific
revolutions. Publishes two papers promoting the possibility of
overcoming the mind-body problem with &ldquo;eliminative
materialism&rdquo;, illustrating why everyday language and common
knowledge should be corrected.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1964</td>
  <td>UCLA Berkeley opens doors to minorities. Actively attempts to
avoid indoctrinating students with Western philosophy. Tries to
promote critical thinking instead.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1965</td>
  <td>&ldquo;Problems of Empiricism&rdquo; expands on his early work.
Discusses issues in foundations of quantum theory with von
Weizs&auml;cker in Hamburg, confronting the uselessness of general,
abstract methodological rules given specific, actual scientific
problems later prompting his &lsquo;skeptical phase&rsquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1967</td>
  <td>&lsquo;Awakes&rsquo; from his &lsquo;dogmatic slumber&rsquo;
after an epiphany: the realization he no longer considers himself a
Popperian. Announces he is breaking from Popper&rsquo;s school to
Popper&rsquo;s school, generalizing from the limited validity of
falsificationism to &lsquo;anything goes&rsquo; (all methodological
rules have only a limited validity), relinquishing his aim to develop
a positive, normative model for acquiring knowledge. Announces he will
use the title &ldquo;Against Method&rdquo; for his new
&lsquo;position&rsquo;. Begins his increasingly poignant derision of
general methodology. Reverses himself on realism, from recommending
correcting common knowledge and everyday language with science to
protecting them from scientism. Concludes happiness, not truth, should
guide our ontological beliefs, beginning his &lsquo;skeptical
phase&rsquo; and his &lsquo;historical turn&rsquo;.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1968</td>
  <td>&ldquo;Science, Freedom and the Good Life&rdquo; criticizes both
Popper and Kuhn and begins explicitly to doubt that science is
promoting happiness. &ldquo;On a Recent Critique of Complementarity.
Part I&rdquo; attacks the dogmatism of the &lsquo;Copenhagen
interpretation&rsquo; and includes a scathing criticism of
Popper&rsquo;s propensity interpretation.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1969</td>
  <td>&ldquo;Linguistic Arguments and Scientific Method&rdquo;
(belatedly) develops his early view that scientific knowledge should
be used to correct common knowledge and everyday language to promote
progress</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1970</td>
  <td>&ldquo;Consolations for the Specialist&rdquo; attacks Popper
from a Kuhnian perspective. Essay version of &ldquo;Against Method:
Outline of an Anarchistic Theory of Knowledge&rdquo; endorses
&ldquo;epistemological anarchism&rdquo; and the slogan &ldquo;Anything
goes!&rdquo;. Applies John Stuart Mill&rsquo;s <em>On Liberty</em> to
scientific methodology.</td> </tr>
<tr>
  <td>1974</td>
  <td>Death of Feyerabend&rsquo;s friend Imre Lakatos, who had
