&lsquo;Post-Modern&rsquo; Themes in Paul Feyerabend&rsquo;s Later
Philosophy of Science&rdquo;, <em>Studies in History and Philosophy of
Science</em>, 29: 425&ndash;447.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2016, &ldquo;The Rise of Western
Rationalism: Paul Feyerabend&rsquo;s Story&rdquo;, <em>Studies in
History and Philosophy of Science</em>, 57: 79&ndash;86.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024, &ldquo;Feyerabend and Mach&rdquo; in
S. Gattei and R. Corvi (eds.), <em>Feyerabend in Dialogue. Boston
Studies in the of Science</em>, vol. 346, Cham: Springer, pp.
59&ndash;91.</li>

<li>Preston, J., Mun&eacute;var, G. and Lamb, D. (eds.), 2000, <em>The
Worst Enemy of Science? Essays in Memory of Paul Feyerabend</em>, New
York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>Putnam, H., 1965, &ldquo;How Not to Talk about Meaning&rdquo;, in
R. Cohen &amp; M. Wartofsky (eds.), <em>Boston Studies in the
Philosophy of Science</em> (Volume 2: In Honor of Philipp Frank), New
York: Humanities Press, pp. 117&ndash;131.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1978, <em>Meaning and the Moral
Sciences</em>, London: Routledge and Kegan Paul.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1981, <em>Reason, Truth, and History</em>,
Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Roe, S.M., 2009, &ldquo;The Attenuated Ramblings of a Madman:
Feyerabend&rsquo;s Anarchy Examined&rdquo;, <em>Polish Journal of
Philosophy</em>, 3: 67&ndash;85.</li>

<li>Sankey, H., 1994, <em>The Incommensurability Thesis</em>,
Aldershot: Avebury Press.</li>

<li>Scheffler, I., 1966, <em>Science and Subjectivity</em>,
Indianapolis: Hackett Publishing Co.</li>

<li>Scheibe, E., 1988, &ldquo;Paul Feyerabend un die rationalen
Rekonstruktionen&rdquo;, in P. Hoyningen-Huene &amp; G. Hirsch (eds.),
<em>Wozu Wissenschaftsphilosophie? Positionen und Fragen zur heutigen
Wissenschaftsphilosophie</em>, Berlin: De Gruyter.</li>

<li>Shapere, D., 1966, &ldquo;Meaning and Scientific Change&rdquo;, in
R. Colodny (ed.), <em>Mind and Cosmos: Essays in Contemporary Science
and Philosophy</em>, Pittsburgh: University of Pittsburgh Press, pp.
41&ndash;85.</li>

<li>Shaw, J., 2017a, &ldquo;Was Feyerabend an Anarchist? The
Structure(s) of &lsquo;Anything Goes&rsquo;&rdquo;, <em>Studies in
History and Philosophy of Science</em>, 64: 11&ndash;21.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2017b, &ldquo;Feyerabend and the Cranks: On
Demarcation, Epistemic Virtues, and Astrology&rdquo;, <em>Social
Epistemology Review and Reply Collective</em>, 6: 74&ndash;88.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020, &ldquo;The Revolt Against
Rationalism: Feyerabend&rsquo;s Critical Philosophy&rdquo;,
<em>Studies in History and Philosophy of Science Part A,</em> 80:
110&ndash;122.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021a, &ldquo;Feyerabend Never Was an
Eliminative Materialist: Feyerabend&rsquo;s Meta-Philosophy and the
Mind&ndash;Body Problem&rdquo; in K. Bschir &amp; J. Shaw (eds.),
2021, pp. 114&ndash;131.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021b, &ldquo;Feyerabend&rsquo;s
Well-Ordered Science: How an Anarchist Distributes Funds&rdquo;,
<em>Synthese</em>, 198: 419&ndash;449.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021c, &ldquo;Feyerabend and Manufactured
Disagreement: Reflections on Expertise, Consensus, and Science
Policy&rdquo;, <em>Synthese,</em> 198: 6053&ndash;6084.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021d, &ldquo;Feyerabend, Funding, and the
Freedom of Science: The Case of Traditional Chinese Medicine&rdquo;,
<em>European Journal for Philosophy of Science</em>, 11: 37.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2021e, &ldquo;Feyerabend on Naturalism,
Pluralism, and the Foundations of Philosophy&rdquo;, <em>Logique et
Analyse,</em> 256: 467&ndash;486.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2022, &ldquo;Feyerabend&rsquo;s Anarchism:
A Political and Epistemological Analysis&rdquo;, <em>Zilsel,</em> 11:
191&ndash;204.</li>

<li>Shaw, J. and Bschir, K., 2021, &ldquo;Introduction: Paul
Feyerabend&rsquo;s Philosophy in the Twenty-First Century&rdquo;, in
J. Shaw &amp; K. Bschir (eds.), 2021, pp. 1&ndash;10.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, (eds.), 2021, <em>Interpreting Feyerabend:
Critical Essays</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Siegel, H., 1989, &ldquo;Farewell to Feyerabend&rdquo;,
<em>Inquiry</em>, 32: 343&ndash;369.</li>

<li>Solomon, M., 2008, &ldquo;Norms of Dissent&rdquo;, in D. Fennell
(ed.), <em>Contingency and Dissent in Science Project Discussion Paper
Series</em>, London School of Economics CPNSS Discussion Paper,
Technical Report 0908.</li>

<li>Sontag, S., 1966, <em>Against Interpretation, and Other
Essays</em>, New York: Farrar, Straus &amp; Giroux.</li>

<li>Sorgner, H., 2016, &ldquo;Challenging Expertise: Paul Feyerabend
vs. Harry Collins &amp; Robert Evans on democracy, public
participation and scientific authority&rdquo;, <em>Studies in History
and Philosophy of Science</em>, 57: 114&ndash;120.</li>

<li>Stadler, F., 2008, &ldquo;Paul Feyerabend and the Forgotten Third
Vienna Circle&rdquo;, in R. Scazzieri and R. Simili (eds.), <em>The
Migration of Ideas</em>, Cambridge, Mass.: Watson, pp.
203&ndash;244.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, <em>The Vienna Circle &ndash; Studies
in the Origins, Development and Influence of Logical Empiricism</em>,
revised edition, Vienna: Springer.</li>

<li>Stadler, F. and Fischer, K. (eds.), 2006, <em>Paul Feyerabend: Ein
Philosoph aus Wien</em>, Vienna: Springer.</li>

<li>Staley, K., 1999, &ldquo;Logic, Liberty, and Anarchy: Mill and
Feyerabend on Scientific Method&rdquo;, <em>The Social Science
Journal</em>, 36: 603&ndash;614.</li>

<li>Suppe, F. (ed.), 1977, <em>The Structure of Scientific
Theories</em>, Urbana: University of Illinois Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1989, <em>The Semantic Conception of
Theories and Scientific Realism</em>, Urbana: University of Illinois
Press.</li>

<li>Szumilewicz, I., 1977, &ldquo;Incommensurability and the
Rationality of the Development of Science&rdquo;, <em>British Journal
for the Philosophy of Science</em>, 28: 345&ndash;350.</li>

<li>Tambolo, L., 2014, &ldquo;Pliability and Resistance: Feyerabendian
Insights into Sophisticated Realism&rdquo;, <em>European Journal for
Philosophy of Science</em>, 4: 197&ndash;213.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2015, &ldquo;A Tale of Three Theories:
Feyerabend and Popper on Progress and the Aim of Science&rdquo;,
<em>Studies in History and Philosophy of Science</em>, 51:
33&ndash;41.</li>

<li>Theocharis, T. and Psimopoulos, M., 1987, &ldquo;Where Science Has
Gone Wrong&rdquo;, <em>Nature</em>, 329: 595&ndash;598.</li>

<li>Thomason, N., 1994, &ldquo;The Power of ARCHED Hypotheses:
Feyerabend&rsquo;s Galileo as a Closet Rationalist&rdquo;, <em>British
Journal for the Philosophy of Science</em>, 45: 255&ndash;264.</li>

<li>Tibbetts, P., 1976, &ldquo;Feyerabend on Ideology, Human
Happiness, and the Good Life&rdquo;, <em>Man and World</em>, 9:
362&ndash;371.</li>

<li>Townsend, B., 1971, &ldquo;Feyerabend&rsquo;s Pragmatic Theory of
Observation and the Comparability of Alternative Theories&rdquo;, in
R. Buck &amp; R. Cohen (eds.), <em>PSA 1970. Boston Studies in the
Philosophy of Science, Volume 8</em>, Dordrecht: D. Reidel, pp.
202&ndash;211.</li>

<li>Trigg, R., 1973, <em>Reason and Commitment</em>, Cambridge:
Cambridge University Press.</li>

<li>Tsou, J., 2003, &ldquo;Reconsidering Feyerabend&rsquo;s
Anarchism&rdquo;, <em>Perspectives on Science: Historical,
Philosophical, Social</em>, 11: 208&ndash;235.</li>

<li>Van Fraassen, B., 1980, <em>The Scientific Image</em>, Oxford:
Clarendon Press.</li>

<li>Van Strien, M., 2020a, &ldquo;Pluralism and Anarchism in Quantum
Physics: Paul Feyerabend&rsquo;s Writings on Quantum Physics in
relation to his General Philosophy of Science&rdquo;, <em>Studies in
History and Philosophy of Science</em>, 80: 72&ndash;81.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2020b, &ldquo;Bohm&rsquo;s Theory of
Quantum Mechanics and the Notion of Classicality&rdquo;, <em>Studies
in History and Philosophy of Modern Physics Part B</em>, 71:
72&ndash;86.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024a, &ldquo;The Challenge of Quantum
Mechanics to the Rationality of Science: Philosophers of Science on
Bohr&rdquo;, <em>International Studies in the Philosophy of
Science</em>, 37(4): 219&ndash;241.
doi:10.1080/02698595.2023.2207404</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2024b, &ldquo;Why Bohm was never a
determinist&rdquo;, in A. Oldofredi (ed.), <em>Guiding Waves in
Quantum Mechanics: 100 Years of de Broglie-Bohm Pilot-Wave
Theory</em>, Oxford: Oxford University Press, pp. 1&ndash;15.</li>

<li>Watkins, J., 1984, <em>Science and Scepticism</em>, New Jersey:
Princeton University Press.</li>

<li>Weckert, J., 1986, &ldquo;The Theory-Ladenness of
Observations&rdquo;, <em>Studies in History and Philosophy of
Science</em>, 17: 115&ndash;127.</li>

<li>Weimer, W., 1980, &ldquo;For and Against Method: Reflections on
Feyerabend and the Foibles of Philosophy&rdquo;, <em>Pre/Text</em>,
1&ndash;2: 161&ndash;203.</li>

<li>Werth, R., 1980, &ldquo;On the Theory-Dependence of
Observations&rdquo;, <em>Studies in History and Philosophy of
Science</em>, 11: 137&ndash;143.</li>

<li>Wisdom, J., 1974, &ldquo;The Incommensurability Thesis&rdquo;,
<em>Philosophical Studies</em>, 25: 299&ndash;301.</li>

<li>Wittgenstein, L., 1953, <em>Philosophical Investigations,</em> G.
Anscombe &amp; R. Rhees (eds.), Oxford: Blackwell.</li>

<li>Worrall, J., 1978a, &ldquo;Against Too Much Method&rdquo;,
<em>Erkenntnis</em>, 13: 279&ndash;295.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1978b, &ldquo;Is the Empirical Content of a
Theory Dependent On Its Rivals?&rdquo; in I. Niiniluoto and R. Tuomela
(eds.), <em>The Logic and Epistemology of Scientific Change</em>.
<em>Acta Philosophica Fennica</em>, <em>Volume 30</em>, pp.
298&ndash;310.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1991, &ldquo;Feyerabend and the
Facts&rdquo;, in Mun&eacute;var (ed.), 1991, pp. 329&ndash;353.</li>

<li>Yates, S., 1984, &ldquo;Feyerabend&rsquo;s Democratic
Relativism&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 27: 137&ndash;142.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1985, &ldquo;More on Democratic Relativism:
A Response to Alford&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 28: 450&ndash;453.</li>

<li>Yuann, J., 2007, &ldquo;A Naturalistic Approach to Scientific
Methodology: A Comparative Study of O. Neurath and P.
Feyerabend&rdquo;, in M. Chienkuo &amp; R. Chen (eds.),
<em>Naturalized Epistemology and Philosophy of Science</em>, Amsterdam
&amp; New York: Rodopi, pp. 171&ndash;196.</li>

<li>Zahar, E., 1977, &ldquo;Mach, Einstein, and the Rise of Modern
Science&rdquo;, <em>British Journal for the Philosophy of
Science</em>, 28: 195&ndash;213.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1978, &ldquo;Theorienkonflikt und die
Steurerung der Erkenntnis&rdquo;, in O. Molden, (ed.), <em>Konflikt
und Ordnung: Europ&auml;isches Forum Alpbach</em>, Vienna: Molden
Verlag, pp. 234&ndash;239.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1981, &ldquo;Second Thoughts About Machian
Positivism: A Reply to Feyerabend&rdquo;, <em>British Journal for the
Philosophy of Science</em>, 32: 267&ndash;276.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1982, &ldquo;Feyerabend on Observation and
Empirical Content&rdquo;, <em>British Journal for the Philosophy of
Science</em>, 33: 397&ndash;409.</li>
</ul>
